MATEP generates steam, chilled water and electricity from the on-site combustion of natural gas and fuel oil for distribution to customers and to supply the MATEP building with steam for space heating, chilled water for space cooling, and electricity for lighting and the operation of equipment not related to energy generation (the MATEP building is analogous to a MATEP "customer"). MATEP also purchases electricity. However, all of the purchased electric power is either consumed by equipment used to generate energy (i.e. chillers) or is passed directly on to customers. Building energy use is calculated based on estimated equipment loads.

MATEP uses water supplied by the Boston Water & Sewer Commission/MWRA to produce boiler feed and chilled water, exhaust waste heat to the atmosphere via evaporation, and operate and cool energy generation equipment. A small portion of this water is also used to supply the building itself for sanitary purposes. Building water use is estimated.

User Submitted Info: The Swimming Pool property use doesn’t have any gross floor area associated with it – it should generally only be used as an add-on to an existing building, so I think the plan of classifying it as a Fitness Center/Health Club/Gym and then adding in the pool is probably the best bet, if the primary use of the building is the fitness center/gym. The tennis courts and climbing walls can be included in that Fitness Center GFA.For the Offices, if they primarily support the fitness center/gym function, they should be included in the same primary Fitness Center GFA. However, if they serve other college departments or functions, you may want to break them out separately as an Office property use. This will affect your whole-building median EUI calculation for comparison, though. I think your benchmarking and tracking plan sounds good as well – while they won’t be able to get a score, comparing themselves against the national median EUI for similar properties can be extremely useful.
